00:37:57,000 --> 00:37:59,000
Time is just time.

430
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:00,000
It always goes forward.

431
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:02,000
Have you ever flown in a craft?

432
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:03,000
Yes.

433
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:04,000
Yeah.

434
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:05,000
A couple of times I did.

435
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:07,000
What was that like?

436
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:29,000
Well, I was in the cargo hold at the time, because there was, as I describe in my books, the day after I thought I'd broken my kneecap and then it healed up, there was the next morning when they came down to get me and take me up to their base, up at area 53, to see if I needed a surgery on my knee.

437
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:30,000
And was it the tall whites?

438
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:31,000
Yeah.

439
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:36,000
And when I got up there, the American generals and medical people were up there, too.

440
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:37,000
And I didn't.

441
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:39,000
I just bruised it.

442
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:46,000
But the tall whites had to prove to the Americans that they were telling them they're correct or wanted to prove that.

443
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:52,000
And so they came down and grabbed me and put me in the hold of the cargo shop.

444
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:56,000
And I still remember the trip up there and the trip back.

445
00:38:56,000 --> 00:38:58,000
Where did they go?

446
00:38:58,000 --> 00:38:59,000
Did you leave?

447
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:05,000
No, they just lifted off and we just went gently up the valley, perhaps 100 feet off the ground.

448
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:15,000
And I remember flying around range fours and made the turn around range four and then going up the valley to the, they were going to the scout craft, the back entrance to their scout craft hangar.

449
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:24,000
And the door was open and we went in there and then there was a whole bunch of them in there, but there were also American, an American general and some American medical people.

450
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:34,000
And the six sergeants, the chief master sergeants that were the human guards for the human generals and the teacher in range four, Harry.

451
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:39,000
And it was just like sitting here in a chair only in the cargo hold.

452
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:42,000
And they didn't do this.

453
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:46,000
They didn't totally power up because they didn't have to.

454
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:54,000
And it was, it was like sitting here in the chair and having the whole room just be lifted up and taken and come back.

455
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:58,000
And it was remarkably unremarkable.

456
00:39:58,000 --> 00:39:59,000
Yeah.

457
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:00,000
Yeah.

458
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:15,000
The important part was that they thought they'd electronically hypnotize me, but their equipment doesn't work if you're sick or if you're angry or if you're really tired.

459
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:23,000
And since I was, even though my knee was not broken, I was still experiencing some pain, you know, it was still tender.

460
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:33,000
It meant that the way my thoughts, the blood flow in the brain was, was somewhat different than the way it would normally be.

461
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:47,000
And so, therefore, when you use the electronic hypnotism on me that would normally have worked when I was ordinary, if I was healthy and well rested, it didn't quite do the job.

462
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:51,000
It's almost like anesthesia that doesn't work during surgery or something.

463
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:52,000
Yeah.

464
00:40:52,000 --> 00:40:53,000
Yeah.

465
00:40:53,000 --> 00:40:55,000
So I got to remember it.

466
00:40:55,000 --> 00:40:56,000
Yeah.

467
00:40:56,000 --> 00:40:59,000
Uh, range four hearing knew that was the case, but that was all he could do.

468
00:40:59,000 --> 00:41:00,000
Yeah.

469
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:02,000
Why do you think they chose you for all of this?

470
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:06,000
Why do you think you were sort of picked to be endowed with this knowledge?

471
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:16,000
One time I asked a different person who was one of the top, identified himself as one of the top three psychiatrists at the CIA.

472
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:20,000
One of the time I asked them why they chose me.

473
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:21,000
Okay.

474
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:31,000
Because I said I thought there were lots of men that were better at going out in the desert and surviving and doing fixing trucks and so on than myself.

475
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:35,000
A lot of weather observers with more experience and so on than me.

476
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:38,000
And he told me the following.

477
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:47,000
He said that, and he had like nine PhDs hanging on the wall for different facets of psychiatry.

478
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:49,000
And he was a very nice guy.

479
00:41:49,000 --> 00:41:52,000
He was surprisingly young, like in his thirties.

480
00:41:52,000 --> 00:42:04,000
He said that when he studied psychiatry, he was told that there was 105 different psychological defenses that humans might use.

481
00:42:04,000 --> 00:42:08,000
The most famous is whistling in the dark.

482
00:42:08,000 --> 00:42:09,000
Okay.

483
00:42:09,000 --> 00:42:15,000
He said that most humans only use one or two at the most.

484
00:42:15,000 --> 00:42:28,000
That one of the projects that he and the others usually did was trying to train colonels and generals on how to have more psychological defenses.

485
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:35,000
They were hoping to get generals to use three or they always want them to use three.

486
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:39,000
They were hoping they could get them to use four or five.

487
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:41,000
This is of the 105.

488
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:52,000
And he said that he had told his, the other guys that were with him, psychiatrists, that some of the, there were a couple of, there were some generals he was trying to train.

489
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:57,000
He thought he was going to get them to learn seven and he couldn't.

490
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:00,000
They were going to hang in there at three.

491
00:43:00,000 --> 00:43:12,000
He said that the first time he met me, he was shocked because in the first 15 minutes, he saw me use the first 70 out of the 105.

492
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:17,000
And he was a certain I could use the other, the remainder of the 105.

493
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:19,000
And you can see it in my books.

494
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:27,000
He said the 41 men that went out before me, who all came back compromised and some of them burned.

495
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:48,000
He said the problem they had in his opinion was that they recognized what they were up against or something of what they were up against before they understood how they were going to, had decided how they were going to react.

496
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:49,000
Okay.

497
00:43:49,000 --> 00:44:02,000
And he said that in, and therefore what happened was in just the first encounter, their psychological defenses got destroyed.

498
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:08,000
And he said that the reason they sent me, he said, if there ever was a person to send, it would be you.

499
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:12,000
He said it's because they'll never lay a glove on you.

500
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:13,000
Yeah.

501
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:20,000
They'll never, that, you know, that no matter what happens, you know, you have a defense for it.

502
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:21,000
Okay.

503
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:24,000
And they had evaluated that prior to sending you out.

504
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:25,000
Yeah.

505
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:26,000
To commune with the 18th.

506
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:27,000
Yeah.

507
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:30,000
They'll let, they have a, you know, and you can see it in there.

508
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:41,000
There was a time when I thought that the extraterrestrials, the extraterrestrial lady I was looking at, that I was hallucinating.

509
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:55,000
And I was kind of surprised because I was kind of thinking that if I was going to hallucinate, I was alone out in the desert, I was young and single, that if I was going to hallucinate, that it would be more like a Las Vegas showgirl.

510
00:44:55,000 --> 00:45:02,000
And she wasn't, you know, and I thought, my God, how sick am I? I'm not even, you know, see.

511
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:08,000
And she was laughing because she could tell that I was thinking because of her electronic equipment, you see.

512
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:22,000
See, and there was a time when I was, there was a time when I thought that I must be short on vitamins when they would come into my barracks at Indian Springs and I would get up and I would see the children playing.

513
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:33,000
And I thought, golly, I knew I should have drank more milk. It's for supper. I must be short on vitamins and milk. And so I would take more vitamins and they would still keep coming. There was a time when I—

514
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:41,780
But you're also debriefing with generals who are admitting that this is a phenomena that they're aware of and that they're kind of working alongside these ETs. Is that right?

515
00:45:41,780 --> 00:45:43,780
Well, I'm never debriefed.

516
00:45:43,780 --> 00:45:44,780
You're never debriefed.

517
00:45:44,780 --> 00:45:46,780
I'm never briefed. I'm never debriefed.

518
00:45:46,780 --> 00:45:47,780
Are you talking to the generals about—

519
00:45:47,780 --> 00:45:54,780
Not only—that's not an accident. My orders are, I can never be briefed. I can never be debriefed.

520
00:45:54,780 --> 00:46:05,780
And the reason is very simple. Because the tall whites, like the teacher, can tell what a person is thinking, even if they're not talking.

521
00:46:05,780 --> 00:46:19,780
Well, if you're debriefed and they're very touchy about their children, if a briefing person were to say, what kind of mother is the teacher?

522
00:46:19,780 --> 00:46:26,780
You know, how does she treat her little girl? I mean, she was lost in the sagebrush and you saved her life. How did they let that happen?

523
00:46:26,780 --> 00:46:35,780
See, then they wouldn't have to ask me to tell them about it. See, they could tell it by just reading my thoughts.

524
00:46:35,780 --> 00:46:47,780
The next thing they would demand is that somebody, like that officer, be delivered to them out in the desert, and he wouldn't live another moment, okay?

525
00:46:47,780 --> 00:46:55,780
Yeah. And I wouldn't have to say anything or do anything or say else, because she could just tell, oh yeah, I read Charlie and I see that happened.

526
00:46:55,780 --> 00:47:03,780
So when I say that no one could ever ask me questions, I could never be debriefed. Nothing I would do would ever be classified.

527
00:47:03,780 --> 00:47:16,780
I mean, they couldn't even inspect me. If they wanted to talk to me, they physically had to come out to the parking out of the chow hall at Indian Springs between noon and 1230.

528
00:47:16,780 --> 00:47:25,780
And I would meet them there if I felt like meeting them, or if I didn't, then they would just, and before they went out, they would have to check in with the base commander at Nellis.

529
00:47:25,780 --> 00:47:38,780
And when they came back, they had to go directly from checking on base to the base commander and say, yeah, I looked healthy and so on. And I could, and they couldn't come out and inspect my barracks or see anything.

530
00:47:38,780 --> 00:47:54,520
Have you, you mentioned the CIA psychiatrist who said that you had all these psychological defenses and that sort of allowed you to enter into relations with the ETs and come back in time.

531
00:47:54,520 --> 00:48:07,480
So it allowed me to protect my thoughts, the person I am, before admitting to myself, they are real and I know what I'm going to do.

532
00:48:07,680 --> 00:48:11,260
Have you ever heard the name Kit Green? Is that familiar to you at all?

533
00:48:11,260 --> 00:48:37,500
Hmm. It doesn't ring a bell, but I probably heard them. But see, like, see, like, like the first thing I agreed, the first agreement I made with them was after realizing they were real, that I asked them that whenever they came around me, that they talk between themselves, if they were talking between themselves or with me in a way that I could hear to speak English,

534
00:48:37,500 --> 00:49:03,200
because it frightened me if they were talking between themselves. And it sometimes sounded like horse winnings or bird calls. And they agreed. And then the second one was that if I saw them out in the desert, like if I came over a rise and there was one sitting on a rock, I understood that it was easy for me to sneak up on them behind them and surprise them. And I didn't want to do that.

535
00:49:03,200 --> 00:49:23,760
And I would just stop where I was and stand where I was and sing a song and let them know I was there. And then if they wanted to come closer, I would just stand there and they could walk up towards me and stop whenever they wanted to.

536
00:49:23,760 --> 00:49:45,500
I wouldn't pursue, I wouldn't pursue, I wouldn't close the gap. And if they got too close to me so that it, I started feeling intimidated, I would start backing away and they would stop. And then when we had decided how far apart we were going to be physically, then we could communicate.

537
00:49:46,140 --> 00:49:51,700
Your wife, Marie-Therese, mentioned that you actually were sent out initially.

538
00:49:51,700 --> 00:50:19,620
Initially, I was supposed to go from, after doing my basic training at Lackland, then I was put in PAT standing. You know, that was airmen waiting their security clearance. Okay. And those airmen that were going to get a security clearance and be sent to San Angeles, Texas for security school 101, were supposed to wait there for like three weeks or so. Okay.

539
00:50:19,620 --> 00:50:29,980
Now, the security clearance you're waiting for is whatever the government decides to give you, but it's supposed to be the top secret clearance. Okay.

540
00:50:29,980 --> 00:50:45,260
Now, the security, the security training, the people who are sent to San Angeles, Texas are waiting to get their orders to San Angeles, Texas.

541
00:50:45,260 --> 00:50:59,500
However, in my case, they've issued two sets of orders, the real ones to San Angeles, Texas, and the cover orders to the weather training school at Shunard Air Force Base, Illinois.

542
00:50:59,500 --> 00:51:15,700
The idea is that the captain, who is in charge of those guys, who has a safe for classified material that's locked, this is 1965, times have all changed since then, he's the one that will give out my orders.

543
00:51:15,700 --> 00:51:27,920
Yes. The day sergeant can give out all the rest of the orders. Okay. Yeah. Because the day sergeant, because my clearance is going to be a higher clearance than theirs.

544
00:51:27,920 --> 00:51:42,880
Well, the Friday that they came in, the captain is off playing golf. Now, as a military officer, he's supposed to be on duty. He's off playing golf and left the sergeant in command.

545
00:51:42,880 --> 00:51:58,840
The sergeant does not have the clearance to know about my orders. So, when the orders come in for everybody else, and we were all in the same class together at boot camp, I think a mistake has been made.

546
00:51:59,680 --> 00:52:11,280
Okay. They get their orders. I go in with them. There's no orders. I say, well, because my cover orders are in a different location than their orders,

547
00:52:11,280 --> 00:52:22,700
but they're not locked up, see? They're just in the temporary outbox. Well, I asked the sergeant, I got no orders. I go into weather school, too.

548
00:52:22,700 --> 00:52:28,900
So, the sergeant goes and gets those orders and says, oh, yeah, here's your orders, and hands them to me to go to weather training school.

549
00:52:28,980 --> 00:52:35,880
So, I go out and I get on the bus. You know, I got my stuff back. Now, my drill sergeant had made a very special point.

550
00:52:35,940 --> 00:52:40,980
He said, anytime you do anything in the military, keep two copies of your orders because you can't trust your officers.

551
00:52:41,860 --> 00:52:50,440
Right? Genius, right? I keep two copies, right? Okay. So, I get on the bus. I'm not in the travel mass, but I got orders.

552
00:52:50,580 --> 00:52:54,760
So, what? So, they throw me on the airplane, and they send me to shoot at Air Force Base, Illinois.

553
00:52:55,020 --> 00:53:01,960
If you can't shoot them, shinoot them, that place. Okay. Well, I'm in the base, and everybody else is getting paid,

554
00:53:01,960 --> 00:53:08,420
and I'm at weather school, and I'm the best student in the class. And after, like, six weeks, I still haven't been paid.

555
00:53:08,420 --> 00:53:16,220
And so, I go, and I ask the command, my immediate commander, can I go see, I'm not getting paid.

556
00:53:16,280 --> 00:53:24,740
He sends me over to the base payroll offices, and they look at their records, and they're panicky.

557
00:53:24,740 --> 00:53:35,600
You're on this base, and they send me back to weather school. I go back to weather school, and two MP air policemen and a dog come in and grab me

558
00:53:35,600 --> 00:53:39,080
and march me over to the base commander's office.

559
00:53:40,840 --> 00:53:43,940
I'm a little terrified, and the base commander says,

560
00:53:44,680 --> 00:53:49,440
Airman Hall, if you have a copy of your orders showing you that you're supposed to be on this base,

561
00:53:49,840 --> 00:53:56,320
then you're going to be a happy man, and whoever gave you the orders is not going to be very happy.

562
00:53:56,320 --> 00:54:02,480
But if you don't have a copy of the orders, the man who gave them to you is going to be a happy man,

563
00:54:02,480 --> 00:54:06,160
and you're not going to be a soldier. You're not going to be a very happy soldier,

564
00:54:06,160 --> 00:54:11,140
because the generals tell me you're too valuable a man to be wasted at this school.

565
00:54:11,900 --> 00:54:17,160
I had two copies in my hall. I said, thank you, Sergeant Matt, you're Sergeant Peoples.

566
00:54:17,440 --> 00:54:20,860
I graced his hand. I said, you need another one. I can copy this, right?

567
00:54:20,860 --> 00:54:26,500
I was a happy man. They said, well, we'll decide what to do, right?

568
00:54:26,980 --> 00:54:31,380
So they'd been looking for me at St. Angels, Texas for six weeks.

569
00:54:31,840 --> 00:54:34,380
The FBI had been looking for me at my house in London.

570
00:54:34,840 --> 00:54:38,320
Nobody had found me. I go back, and the sergeant comes out and says,

571
00:54:38,420 --> 00:54:40,220
You're going to Nellis, okay?

572
00:54:40,600 --> 00:54:40,980
Wow.

573
00:54:41,260 --> 00:54:46,000
Yeah. They gave me the usual wish list.

574
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:50,180
When you finish weather school, name three places you'd like to go.

575
00:54:50,180 --> 00:54:56,220
I said, Germany, England, and March Air Force Base, Los Angeles.

576
00:54:56,360 --> 00:54:57,960
And I said, no, you're going to Nellis.

577
00:54:58,300 --> 00:55:03,580
How soon after you're stationed at Nellis do you encounter this abandoned weather station

578
00:55:03,580 --> 00:55:05,800
and meet your first tall white?

579
00:55:07,740 --> 00:55:14,240
Well, the first time that I heard tell of the tall whites at Nellis

580
00:55:14,240 --> 00:55:22,580
was that my very first duty session had Nellis with another airman,

581
00:55:22,780 --> 00:55:25,760
which I describe in my book, okay?

582
00:55:25,840 --> 00:55:29,320
He was the airman that had been on leave for several weeks

583
00:55:29,320 --> 00:55:34,340
because he claimed the Nellis weather station was haunted.

584
00:55:34,340 --> 00:55:37,660
And it's not the one you see there today.

585
00:55:38,140 --> 00:55:43,400
It was the old one that was the northeast end of the base operations building.

586
00:55:44,020 --> 00:55:47,580
The base operations building was a very nice building for its day,

587
00:55:47,700 --> 00:55:49,020
as was the weather station.

588
00:55:49,520 --> 00:55:51,140
I describe it in my book.

589
00:55:51,480 --> 00:55:53,740
And it had something very important.

590
00:55:53,860 --> 00:55:57,300
It was the military version of an airport terminal.

591
00:55:57,300 --> 00:56:00,180
And it had something very important.

592
00:56:00,840 --> 00:56:02,920
It had clean restrooms.

593
00:56:03,960 --> 00:56:09,420
The next clean restroom was a mile away in a group of barracks they were still building.

594
00:56:10,020 --> 00:56:14,180
To get to another clean restroom, you had to go a mile and a half away, okay?

595
00:56:14,520 --> 00:56:19,020
He claimed that when he was working NYCHA graveyard,

596
00:56:19,740 --> 00:56:24,520
and he had been in its military, he was on his fourth year,

597
00:56:24,520 --> 00:56:31,460
the previous swimmer that he thought ghosts,

598
00:56:31,940 --> 00:56:35,760
you and I would say a group of five tall white aliens,

599
00:56:35,980 --> 00:56:41,100
had come in off the runway, off the tarmac,

600
00:56:41,680 --> 00:56:47,140
unlocking the glass doors between the base operations,

601
00:56:47,260 --> 00:56:49,840
the interior of the base operations building, the tarmac,

602
00:56:50,160 --> 00:56:53,400
because one of the force fields will make every piece of material

603
00:56:53,400 --> 00:56:56,920
repel every other piece of material and just pop every lock open.

604
00:56:57,700 --> 00:57:02,740
And that when he came in, there was one waiting outside, standing guard,

605
00:57:02,880 --> 00:57:04,400
one holding the door open,

606
00:57:05,200 --> 00:57:08,300
and then that's two men,

607
00:57:08,700 --> 00:57:13,960
and then three women, one holding open the door to the bathroom,

608
00:57:14,640 --> 00:57:16,000
another one inside,

609
00:57:16,740 --> 00:57:19,200
helping them hold open the door to the bathroom,

610
00:57:19,200 --> 00:57:22,440
while the third one was using the ladies' restroom,

611
00:57:22,880 --> 00:57:25,640
and that they were rotating so that they'd come in to use the restroom.

612
00:57:26,180 --> 00:57:29,300
He didn't, he, although he described them doing that,

613
00:57:29,820 --> 00:57:32,220
he didn't appreciate what he was describing.

614
00:57:32,900 --> 00:57:34,240
He thought they were ghosts.

615
00:57:34,380 --> 00:57:36,880
He panicked immediately and started screaming,

616
00:57:37,400 --> 00:57:38,800
locked himself in the doorway,

617
00:57:38,800 --> 00:57:42,780
and called the base air police,

618
00:57:43,020 --> 00:57:46,540
only to discover that the Nellis base commander said,

619
00:57:46,680 --> 00:57:52,240
no, the air police cannot come beyond the road junction a mile away.

620
00:57:52,560 --> 00:57:53,660
He's on his own.

621
00:57:54,180 --> 00:57:54,340
Okay?

622
00:57:54,860 --> 00:57:58,460
Now, I know from firsthand experience that he was telling the truth,

623
00:57:58,920 --> 00:58:03,080
